    <item>
      <title>Easier strace of scripts with pidof -x</title>
      <link>https://purpleidea.com/blog/2013/10/26/easier-strace-of-scripts-with-pidof-x/</link>
      <pubDate>Sat, 26 Oct 2013 16:02:12 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://purpleidea.com/blog/2013/10/26/easier-strace-of-scripts-with-pidof-x/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Here&amp;rsquo;s a &lt;span style=&#34;text-decoration:underline;&#34;&gt;one minute read&lt;/span&gt;, about a trick which I discovered today:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;When running an &lt;em&gt;strace&lt;/em&gt;, it&amp;rsquo;s common to do something like:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;background-color:#f8f8f8;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-fallback&#34; data-lang=&#34;fallback&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;strace -p&amp;lt;pid&amp;gt;&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Smarter hackers know that they can use some bash magic and do:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;background-color:#f8f8f8;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-fallback&#34; data-lang=&#34;fallback&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;strace -p`pidof &amp;lt;process name&amp;gt;`&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;However, if you&amp;rsquo;re tracing a script named &lt;em&gt;foo.py&lt;/em&gt;, this won&amp;rsquo;t work because the real process is the script&amp;rsquo;s interpreter, and &lt;em&gt;pidof python&lt;/em&gt;, might return other unrelated python scripts.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;background-color:#f8f8f8;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-fallback&#34; data-lang=&#34;fallback&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;strace -p`pidof foo.py` # won&amp;#39;t work&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;[failure]&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;[user sifting through ps output for real pid]&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;[computer explodes]&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;The trick is to use the &lt;em&gt;-x&lt;/em&gt; flag of &lt;em&gt;pidof&lt;/em&gt;. This will let you pass in your script&amp;rsquo;s name, and &lt;em&gt;pidof&lt;/em&gt; will take care of the rest:&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
